pr_review_body:
@dpeng817 re: cross-dagster-version compatibility
I updated this PR to switch to another approach (which is even less elegant but easier to roll back). I view this approach of adding op_selection_data to ExternalPipeline a short-term hot fix which I'm not sure about its long term and we may eventually remove. So if we move forward that, even if this PR doesn't cause the compatibility issue, at the time we remove that short-term fix (i.e. removing op_selection_data from ExternalPipeline), it for sure would cause the cross-dagster-version issue.

So, the other direction here is to do the same as pipeline definition [1] -- thread in "parent job def" so ExternalPipeline can pass the right selection info: https://github.com/dagster-io/dagster/blob/master/python_modules/dagster/dagster/core/host_representation/external.py#L242

it looks like this PR also fixes a bug with accessing the iterator when the iterator is an empty list literal, ex.
```vyper
@external
def foo():
    xs: DynArray[uint256,3] = [1,2,3]
    ret: uint256 = 0 # len([1, 2, 3])
    for ys in [[], []]:
        ret += len(ys)
```
please add a test, other than that this is looking pretty good. thanks!

@mfikes huge and high quality contribution.
Thanks a lot.
I put two minor remarks, could you please have a look.

Interesting approach, but I'm concerned that this strategy may not scale in terms of API design. Perhaps we should create an optional args bag as the last parameter? I have a feeling we will continue to add more knobs here as we flesh out gallery and 3p multi-lang components. 

for typescript:

```ts
    async installPlugin(name: string, version: string, kind = "resource", args?: PluginArgs ): Promise<void> {
        let cliArgs = ["plugin", "install", kind, name, version];
        if(args) {
        cliArgs.push("--server");
        cliArgs.push(server);
        }
        await this.runPulumiCmd(cliArgs);
    }

export interface PluginArgs {
    server?: string;
}
```

Go will require a more involved incantation to use functional options. You can use `LocalWorkspaceOptions` as an example.

@vfdev-5 Thanks for the PR.

I added one suggestion to improve BC during the deprecation period and marked all the places where this could happen. Nevertheless, if our policy is typically to only throw warnings feel free to ignore.

Also I noticed that in some methods you throw warnings while in others you directly replace the names. I assume that this is because the first are considered public API while the latter not. If that's true, then all good.

One inline comment about maybe adding `.[test]`, but it currently works, so it is fine.

Let's try Jenkins again:

@jenkins-plone-org please run jobs

@Frassle I've moved the checks as far down as the engine can be aware of whether it's a `destroy/refresh/update`.

`pkg/engine` knows whether something is an `destroy/refresh/update`
the next layer `pkg/resource/deploy` only sees things as `deployments`

@seemethere Thanks for the PR.

Though I agree that cost saving is very important, the proposed changes seem very restrictive. For example we just lost the windows GPU unit-tests, was this accidental? Moreover we lost the ability to check for issues caused by dependencies for specific OS and Python version combinations. Such issues are extremely common at the moment (see for example this from yesterday: #5451). 

I know that your team has on their roadmap a project to standardize and harden the CI infra cross domains. I'm certain that this will help us reduce the breakages. Shall we review the unit-test jobs once this is completed? Happy to chat offline and summarize here later if that's easier. Thanks!
